Remember: Trusting statistical indices alone can be deceptive. You must always plot the data first, and then you perform statistics if visually it makes sense to do so.

Credits: Anscombe (1973)

In our case, we plot the data to visually assess if there's any correlation at all. In this case, we will correlate yield with electrical conductivity like in the pre-class.

Task 1:

In your pre-class, you were tasked with add labels to the yield-vs-ECa plots and make them easier to read. Below is a possible way to make such plots.

Run the cell and read carefully each line.

In[5]:
fs = 15
xlabels = ['Veris Shallow', 'Veris Deep', 'EM38']
colors = ['#FF0000', '#1E88E5', '#004D40']
markers = ['o', 'D', 's']

fig, ax = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(12,3.5), sharex=False, sharey=True)
for i in range(len(ax)):
    ax[i].scatter(electric[:, i], mean_yield, alpha=0.2, c=colors[i], marker=markers[i]);
    ax[i].set_xlabel(xlabels[i], fontsize=0.8*fs)
    ax[i].tick_params(labelsize=0.75*fs)
    ax[i].set_facecolor('whitesmoke')
    
fig.supylabel('Mean Yield [kg/ha]', fontsize=fs)
fig.supxlabel('Soil Electrical Conductivity [mS/m]', fontsize=fs)
fig.suptitle('Centralia, MO (1997 -- 2004)', fontsize=fs)

fig.tight_layout()

Part 2: Computing correlation indices

As you read in the pre-class, one of the most common ways to measure correlation is through the Pearson correlation coefficient. We can compute it in Python, with the pearsonr function from the SciPy's stats module.

Task 2:

Run the following cell below and explain in your own words what the different numbers and results mean. Your instructor should give you a quick rundown of the statistics at the start of the class. Raise your hand if this is not the case.

In[6]:
# Run this cell
# Correlation between average yield and VSh electrical conductivity

corr = stats.pearsonr(electric[:, 0], mean_yield)
conf = corr.confidence_interval(0.95)

print('The Pearson Correlation Index is', corr.statistic)
print('With a p-value of', corr.pvalue, '\n---')
print('With 95% of confidence, the true correlation value lies somewhere between\n',conf.low,'\tand\t', conf.high)

Moral of the story: context matters

You probably observed that by just taking corn, now our correlation indices improved quite a bit. We went from 0.4 to 0.5. Ask yourself the following questions:

  • Do our results imply that corn is more sensitive to soil electrical conductivity than soybean?
  • Does it make sense to compare corn and soybean when we only have 3 years of corn data (as opposed to five from soybean)
  • Both crops were not grown independently. They were rotating crops in the same field. Crop rotation is important and common. Does it make sense to separate the crops in the first place? Should we stick to the initial 8-year average?

Your answers

The true answer here does not depend on statistics. The true answer depends on agronomy (or domain knowledge in general). Python and statistics will process whatever data we throw at them, but the results will be meaningless if the way we split the data is agronomically wrong. Maybe there is no causation and the whole correlation discussion is moot!

Remember: correlation does not imply causation

Fortunately in our case, there is evidence for causation

Apparent profile soil electrical conductivity (ECa) provides an indirect measure of soil physical and chemical properties (McNeill, 1992, Rhoades et al., 1999), properties that can have a dominant influence on plant growth and yield (Jaynes et al., 1995, Lund et al., 2001, Zhang and Taylor, 2001, Kitchen et al., 2003). Characterization of soil variability can be improved by utilizing ECa measurements obtained from different types of ECa sensors (Sudduth et al., this issue). For claypan soils of the U.S. Midwest, ECa has been found to be highly correlated with topsoil thickness (i.e., depth to the Bt horizon) (Doolittle et al., 1994, Sudduth et al., 2001). This soil property causes variation in infiltration and water storage characteristics (Jamison et al., 1968) and is highly related to yield variation in crop growth years with average and below average precipitation (Kitchen et al., 1999). Previous analyses attempting to account for within-field yield variation were improved by including elevation with ECa measurements (Kitchen et al., 2003).

Taken from Kitchen et al (2005), the paper where this electrical conductivity and yield data set comes from.

The bottom line is: statistics and Python can only do so much. True data science always has to be accompanied by domain knowledge.
